## How each security requirement is met

| Requirement | Implementation |
|---|---|
| **SQL injection** | Every query is a `better-sqlite3` prepared statement with bound params (`src/models.js`) — no string concatenation. |
| **Password hashing** | bcrypt (cost 12, per-password salt) via `bcryptjs` (`auth.js`, `create-owner.js`). |
| **Input validation** | `express-validator` rules on credentials and projects; URLs restricted to `http(s)` only (blocks `javascript:`/`data:`). |
| **XSS / output encoding** | EJS auto-escaping (`<%= %>`) everywhere + strict **CSP** with no inline scripts (I moved the delete-confirm into `public/js/app.js`). |
| **CSRF** | Synchronizer token in session, required on all non-safe methods, compared with `crypto.timingSafeEqual` (`middleware/csrf.js`). |
| **Access control / IDOR** | Admin routes require auth; every lookup checks `owner_id === currentUser.id`, and UPDATE/DELETE are also `WHERE owner_id = ?` (defence in depth). Non-owned → indistinguishable 404. |
| **Secure cookies** | `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Lax`, `Secure` when `COOKIE_SECURE=true`; session regenerated on login (anti-fixation). |
| **Security headers** | Helmet (CSP, X-Content-Type-Options, Referrer-Policy, frame-ancestors `none`, etc.). |
| **No leaked errors** | Central error handler logs server-side only; clients get generic messages, never stack traces. |
| **No hardcoded secrets** | All secrets from env via `dotenv`; fail-fast if missing. |

Extras: login rate limiting, generic auth errors (no user enumeration), request body size limits, image stored as a validated URL (no file-upload attack surface — noted in the README).

